{
  "id": "custody-key-control",
  "name": "Key Custody",
  "desc": "Control sits in a cryptographic secret or access key rather than physical possession. Digital custody can be stronger than physical custody when architecture enforces access — but the asset is not held or owed in any traditional sense.",
  "picks": {
    "Capability Class": {
      "value": "Tool-grade",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key analysis applies to tool-grade systems where the custody architecture matters more than frontier capability levels.",
      "detail": "Tool-grade capability is the diagnostic baseline because the custody argument does not depend on superhuman capability. The architecture point holds whether the system is narrow or frontier. What matters is not how capable the system is but who controls access to its capability through cryptographic means. The custody-by-key pattern applies across capability levels, making tool-grade the natural illustrative baseline."
    },
    "Domain Breadth": {
      "value": "Single-domain",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key is illustrated in single-domain contexts where the access control architecture is cleanly separable from domain complexity.",
      "detail": "Single-domain focus keeps the custody analysis clean by isolating the access control architecture from cross-domain complexity. The key-control principle applies regardless of domain breadth but is most clearly demonstrated in bounded contexts. Domain breadth does not change the fundamental claim that cryptographic custody can be stronger than physical custody. The single-domain pick emphasizes that this is an architecture argument, not a capability argument."
    },
    "Capability Trajectory": {
      "value": "Incremental",
      "memo": "The custody-by-key pattern operates under incremental trajectory because the architecture argument is independent of capability acceleration dynamics.",
      "detail": "Incremental trajectory means the custody architecture does not depend on rapid capability change for its relevance. The key-control pattern works the same whether capability is static or improving. This pick signals that the stance is about architectural control, not about racing to contain explosive capability. The custody argument is structural and persistent, not tied to any particular pace of technological change."
    },
    "Research Automation": {
      "value": "Human-led",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key operates in human-led research contexts where the architecture question is about access control design, not recursive capability.",
      "detail": "Human-led research is the baseline because the custody-by-key argument is not about AI research dynamics. The architecture of cryptographic control does not depend on who leads research or how fast capability improves. This pick grounds the stance in the present reality where humans design and implement the custody architecture. The research automation level does not change the structural claim about key-based versus physical custody."
    },
    "Unhobbling": {
      "value": "Tool-using",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key applies to tool-using systems where the key architecture gates what tools and data the system can access and operate upon.",
      "detail": "Tool-using unhobbling means the system accesses external functions through controlled interfaces that key architecture can gate. The key is literally the mechanism that grants or denies the system's access to tools and data stores. This pick demonstrates that cryptographic custody is practically relevant to real deployment configurations, not just theoretical. The tool-using level makes the access control architecture concretely operational rather than abstract."
    },
    "Replication Scale": {
      "value": "Single instance",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key is most clearly illustrated with single-instance systems where key control directly corresponds to control over the specific instance.",
      "detail": "Single instance simplifies the custody analysis by creating a direct correspondence between key possession and system access. With multiple copies, key management becomes a distributed coordination problem rather than a clean custody demonstration. The single-instance pick emphasizes the architectural purity of the custody-by-key concept. Key control of a single instance is the clearest expression of digital custody as an alternative to physical possession."
    },
    "Operating Speed": {
      "value": "Human-speed",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key operates at human-speed where key management ceremonies and access authorization can proceed with adequate deliberation.",
      "detail": "Human-speed operation means key management, authorization, and access ceremonies can occur at a pace that permits deliberate human oversight. This contrasts with scenarios where machine-speed operation would outpace the key management ceremony itself. Human-speed keeps the custody architecture practically manageable and the access decisions humanly reviewable. The operating speed reinforces that this is an architecture about deliberate control, not about speed."
    },
    "Physical World Extension": {
      "value": "Cognitive-only",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key applies to cognitive-only systems where the custody question is purely about access to digital capability and data.",
      "detail": "Cognitive-only extension means the custody question is entirely about digital access rather than physical-world actuation control. This focus sharpens the contrast between physical custody of a medium and cryptographic custody of a capability or dataset. The absence of physical extension makes the custody argument purely architectural and information-theoretic. Cognitive-only is the natural domain for demonstrating that digital custody can exceed physical custody in strength."
    },
    "Role": {
      "value": "Tool",
      "memo": "The custody-by-key system functions as a tool where access is gated by key possession rather than by physical proximity or organizational role.",
      "detail": "Tool role means the system remains directed by its operator and does not exercise independent agency or judgment. The custody question is about who can direct the tool, not about what the tool might do autonomously. Key possession determines who has practical access to the tool's capability, making it the operative control mechanism. Tool role keeps the custody analysis focused on access architecture rather than alignment or autonomy concerns."
    },
    "Actuation": {
      "value": "Digital action",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key gates digital action channels where cryptographic authorization controls what operations the system can execute on digital assets.",
      "detail": "Digital action means the system can execute consequential operations on data, accounts, or digital resources when authorized by key. The actuation channel is gated by the custody architecture, making key possession the prerequisite for any consequential system action. This pick demonstrates that custody-by-key is not merely theoretical but controls real operational capability. Digital action is where the practical power of cryptographic custody becomes economically and operationally meaningful."
    },
    "Autonomy": {
      "value": "Stateless task",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key is demonstrated with stateless tasks where each operation requires fresh key-based authorization without persistent autonomous goals.",
      "detail": "Stateless task means each system operation requires explicit key-based authorization without carrying forward persistent state or goals. This architecture prevents the system from accumulating autonomous capability beyond what each authorized session permits. Stateless operation is the cleanest expression of custody-by-key because control is re-established at each interaction. The stateless character means key custody is continuously operative, not a one-time access grant."
    },
    "Delegated Authority": {
      "value": "Limited mandate",
      "memo": "Key possession delegates a limited operational mandate where the scope of authority is architecturally bounded by what the key permits.",
      "detail": "Limited mandate means the key grants access to a defined scope of operations, not unlimited authority over the system. The key architecture can encode permission boundaries that limit what the holder can do even with valid key possession. This demonstrates that cryptographic custody provides not just access control but authority scoping and boundary enforcement. Limited mandate through key design is a more precise delegation mechanism than most contractual authority frameworks."
    },
    "Tool Access": {
      "value": "Gated tools",
      "memo": "Cryptographic keys serve as the gates controlling which tools and functions the system can access, making key architecture the operative access mechanism.",
      "detail": "Gated tools means each tool or function the system can access requires cryptographic authorization to operate. The keys literally implement the tool access policy at the architectural level rather than through policy documents or contractual terms. This gating mechanism is what makes custody-by-key practically effective rather than merely conceptually interesting. Gated tool access through keys is the operational expression of the principle that architecture enforces access."
    },
    "Response / Intervention Capability": {
      "value": "Kill switch",
      "memo": "Key revocation or rotation serves as the practical kill switch, immediately severing access when custody needs to be transferred or terminated.",
      "detail": "Kill switch through key revocation means access can be immediately terminated by revoking or rotating the controlling cryptographic key. This is faster, more reliable, and more verifiable than physical intervention or contractual termination. Key revocation provides a clean, auditable, and instant shutdown mechanism that physical custody cannot match. The kill switch capability demonstrates that digital custody provides stronger intervention options than physical possession."
    },
    "Command Actor": {
      "value": "Enterprise",
      "memo": "Key custody typically resides with enterprise-level governance where institutional key management policies determine who holds and can exercise control.",
      "detail": "Enterprise command means the organization's key management governance determines who controls system access and capability. This is more structured than informal user control but does not require state-level authority for the custody architecture to function. Enterprise-level key management provides the institutional infrastructure needed for secure custody including ceremony, audit, and succession. The command actor pick reflects that custody-by-key is primarily an enterprise architecture pattern."
    },
    "Decision Tempo": {
      "value": "Product cycle",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key operates at product-cycle decision tempo where key management and access governance follow normal institutional planning timelines.",
      "detail": "Product cycle tempo means key management decisions are made through normal institutional governance processes without crisis urgency. Key rotation schedules, access reviews, and custody transfers follow planned timelines rather than emergency protocols. This tempo is appropriate because the custody architecture operates as a steady-state control mechanism rather than a crisis response. Product-cycle tempo enables the deliberate ceremony that good key management practices require."
    },
    "Tradeoff Authority": {
      "value": "Product team",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key access tradeoffs are typically made by product teams who design the key architecture and determine access policy boundaries.",
      "detail": "Product team authority means the individuals who design and implement the key architecture make the practical tradeoffs. These include decisions about key granularity, rotation frequency, multi-signature requirements, and recovery procedures. The product team's design choices determine the actual strength of the custody architecture in practice. Tradeoff authority at the product team level is appropriate for enterprise-grade custody that does not involve national security stakes."
    },
    "Permission": {
      "value": "Conditional",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key grants conditional permission where access requires valid cryptographic authorization that can be revoked or modified architecturally.",
      "detail": "Conditional permission means access is not blanket but requires ongoing cryptographic validation at each use. The conditions are enforced by the architecture itself rather than by contractual terms or organizational policies alone. Permission can be revoked, scoped, time-limited, or made conditional on external attestation through key design. Conditional permission through cryptography is more reliable than conditional permission through contract because enforcement is automatic."
    },
    "Regulatory Posture": {
      "value": "Conditional",
      "memo": "Cryptographic custody operates under conditional regulatory posture where key management must comply with security standards and data protection requirements.",
      "detail": "Conditional regulation means key management must meet specified security standards, audit requirements, and compliance obligations. The regulatory framework increasingly recognizes cryptographic custody as a legitimate control mechanism with specific compliance requirements. Key management standards, hardware security module certification, and audit trail requirements all create regulatory conditions. Compliance with these conditions is verifiable through the architecture itself rather than through self-declaration alone."
    },
    "Data Availability": {
      "value": "Licensed",
      "memo": "In custody-by-key arrangements, data availability is licensed with access controlled through cryptographic authorization rather than physical distribution.",
      "detail": "Licensed availability means the data exists and is technically accessible but access requires cryptographic authorization from the custodian. The licensing is enforced architecturally through encryption and key management rather than through contractual terms alone. This demonstrates the key insight that custody-by-key separates data availability from data access through architectural enforcement. Licensed availability with cryptographic control is the most precise form of data access management available."
    },
    "Provenance": {
      "value": "Verifiable",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key enables verifiable provenance through cryptographic signing, attestation chains, and tamper-evident logs of all access events.",
      "detail": "Verifiable provenance means every access event, data operation, and custody transfer can be cryptographically signed and verified. The key architecture provides the infrastructure for provenance tracking that is tamper-evident and independently verifiable. This is stronger than declared provenance because the verification is mathematical rather than trust-based. Verifiable provenance through cryptographic custody is one of the strongest arguments for key-based over physical custody."
    },
    "Model-Weight Rights": {
      "value": "Dedicated instance",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key protects a dedicated model instance where the key holder controls access to specific weights isolated from any shared environment.",
      "detail": "Dedicated instance means the key controls access to a specific isolated model deployment rather than shared infrastructure. The key architecture ensures that only authorized parties can access or use the dedicated model weights. This isolation through key control is the model-weight expression of the custody-by-key principle. Dedicated instance with key-controlled access provides stronger custody than dedicated instance with physical-only access controls."
    },
    "Territory": {
      "value": "Cross-border",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key operates across borders because cryptographic control is jurisdiction-independent, functioning regardless of physical data location.",
      "detail": "Cross-border operation demonstrates that cryptographic custody transcends physical territorial boundaries entirely. The key holder controls access regardless of where the data or system physically resides. This is both a strength and a regulatory challenge, as jurisdiction may claim authority over data that key custody places beyond its reach. Cross-border key custody shows that digital custody and territorial jurisdiction can be architecturally decoupled."
    },
