      "value": "Ordinary personal data",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key commonly protects ordinary personal data where the key architecture prevents unauthorized access more reliably than physical controls.",
      "detail": "Ordinary personal data is the baseline exposure level where custody-by-key demonstrates practical value for everyday data protection. The key architecture prevents unauthorized access even by parties with physical access to the storage medium. This directly illustrates the custody essay's claim that custody of the medium is a red herring when data can be copied. Cryptographic key custody provides stronger personal data protection than physical custody of storage devices."
    },
    "Data Sensitivity": {
      "value": "Commercial confidential",
      "memo": "Custody-by-key protects commercially confidential data where the key architecture enforces access boundaries that contractual confidentiality alone cannot guarantee.",
      "detail": "Commercial confidential sensitivity means the data has significant commercial value and requires protection from competitors and unauthorized parties. Key-based custody provides stronger protection than contractual confidentiality because the enforcement is architectural rather than legal. Breach of key-based custody requires cryptographic compromise rather than merely violating a contractual term. Commercial confidential data is where the practical superiority of architectural custody over contractual custody is most commercially relevant."
    },
    "Control Exposure": {
